    <h1 class="big-heading">Current Prevention Efforts</h1>

    <p>

        Numerous initiatives are underway in the US to prevent drug abuse. These include:

    </p>

    <ul class="resources-ul">

        <li>
            
            Medication-Assisted Treatment (MAT): This treatment approach has been shown to be effective in reducing opioid
            use and preventing overdose. Given the ongoing opioid epidemic in the US, expanding access to MAT is critical.

        </li>

        <li>
            
            Prescription Drug Monitoring Programs (PDMPs): These programs can help identify patients who may be at risk for
            substance abuse by tracking the prescribing and dispensing of controlled substances.

        </li>

        <li>

            Naloxone Distribution Programs: Naloxone is a medication that can reverse an opioid overdose. Expanding access
            to naloxone can help save lives in the event of an overdose.

        </li>

        <li>

            National Drug Control Strategy: The government's comprehensive approach to reducing drug abuse and its
            consequences includes prevention efforts, such as education and community-based programs, as well as law
            enforcement and treatment initiatives.
            
        </li>

        <li>

            Drug-Free Workplace Programs: Many employers have implemented drug-free workplace programs, which may include
            drug testing, employee education, and employee assistance programs (EAPs) to help employees who may be
            struggling with substance abuse.

        </li>

        <li>

            School-Based Prevention Programs: Many schools have implemented prevention programs that aim to educate students
            about the risks of drug abuse and help them develop healthy coping skills.

        </li>

        <li>

            Community Anti-Drug Coalitions: Community anti-drug coalitions are groups of community members who work together
            to prevent substance abuse among young people.

        </li>

        <li>

            Prescription Drug Take-Back Programs: These programs provide a safe and convenient way for individuals to
            dispose of unused prescription medications.

        </li>

        <li>

            Substance Abuse and Mental Health Services Administration (SAMHSA): SAMHSA is a federal agency that provides
            funding for substance abuse prevention programs and treatment services, as well as resources and training for
            prevention professionals.

        </li>

        <li>

            National Prevention Week (NPW): This annual event held in May promotes community involvement, resource sharing,
            and partnership engagement to increase public awareness of substance use and mental disorders.
            
        </li>

    </ul>

